Unsupervised machine learning in Sklearn¶

In this project I use principal component analysis and k-means clustering to visualize data. I wanted to understand and visualize the differences and similarities between sets of data. The dataset I'll be working on is playing card decks scraped from online tournament postings.

import sqlite3

df_deck = pd.read_sql_query('SELECT main_deck.uuid, main_deck.cardname, main_deck.quantity FROM MAIN_DECK, deck_meta where main_deck.uuid = deck_meta.uuid and deck_meta.format = "pauper"',con)

my deck data is stored in a sql database using a uuid for each deck, the card name, and the quantity of that card in the deck.

pca_data = pca.transform(dm)

Dimensionality reduction¶

As it stands, my array contains 746 individual cards. To create a visualizion, I need to first reduce the number of dimensions. Sklearn's PCA feature looks at the matrix provided, and reduces the dimensions of the data by compressing that dataset and finding "directions of maximum variance." In plain english, PCA finds subsections of the data which most contribute to variance in the data. For this project I end up graphing the first three principal components in matplotlib, in 3D.

In [32]:
per_var = np.round(pca.explained_variance_ratio_* 100, decimals=1)
labels = ['PC' + str(x) for x in range(1, len(per_var)+1)]
 
plt.bar(x=range(1,len(per_var)+1), height=per_var, tick_label=labels)
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Explained Variance')
plt.xlabel('Principal Component')
plt.title('Scree Plot')
plt.show()

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
In [36]:
x = np.array([[pca_df.PC1[i], pca_df.PC2[i], pca_df.PC3[i]] for i in range(len(pca_df.PC1))])
In [37]:
WCSS = []
for i in range(1,11):
    model = KMeans(n_clusters = i,init = 'k-means++')
    model.fit(x)
    WCSS.append(model.inertia_)
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (7,7))
plt.plot(range(1,11),WCSS, linewidth=4, markersize=12,marker='o',color = 'red')
plt.xticks(np.arange(11))
plt.xlabel("Number of clusters")
plt.ylabel("WCSS")
plt.show()

K-means clustering¶

To cluster the data into different archtypes, I used k-means clustering. This is a method of segmenting data, like the name implies, to find a fixed(k) number of homogenous subgroups.

In [39]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15,15))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.scatter(x[y_clusters == 0,0],x[y_clusters == 0,1],x[y_clusters == 0,2], s = 40 , color = 'blue', label = "cluster 0")
ax.scatter(x[y_clusters == 1,0],x[y_clusters == 1,1],x[y_clusters == 1,2], s = 40 , color = 'orange', label = "cluster 1")
ax.scatter(x[y_clusters == 2,0],x[y_clusters == 2,1],x[y_clusters == 2,2], s = 40 , color = 'green', label = "cluster 2")
ax.scatter(x[y_clusters == 3,0],x[y_clusters == 3,1],x[y_clusters == 3,2], s = 40 , color = '#D12B60', label = "cluster 3")
ax.scatter(x[y_clusters == 4,0],x[y_clusters == 4,1],x[y_clusters == 4,2], s = 40 , color = 'purple', label = "cluster 4")
ax.set_xlabel('pc1')
ax.set_ylabel('pc2')
ax.set_zlabel('pc3')
ax.legend()
plt.show()
